review_blob: This is one of New Hollands strongest offerings.  In fact, I dont remember liking any of their beers more than this.  It pours dark amber with a slight, but lingering head.  The nose is cocoa, pipe tobacco, bourbon, and chili pepper.  The layering of the nose is my favorite part.  Then the taste...  The chili pepper cuts through its butterscotch sweetness, and then fades into the background.  The taste stays, and doesnt let me forget it was there.

22oz bottle.  Small to average head settles into good lacing.  Cloudless amber/orange body.  Cedar and apricot on the nose.  Roasted malt?  Well balanced maltiness to hoppiness.  Hops are pine and citrus.  Alcohol is there, but doesnt burn.  Nice finish.
beer_name: Lagunitas A Little Sumpin Extra! Ale

review_blob: 330ml bottle.  Pours a lightly cloudy, medium, amber body and small head.  Fair lacing.  Malty, nutty caramel cut by hops reminiscent of spruce.  Yeast suggests broth and dough.  Slight clove and banana.  Pair with a game bird.  Pheasant would be delicious.
Clear amber/orange to red with sparse white head.  Nose is grain, orange, and allspice.  Taste some grain and honey, chicken broth, ginger.  Bitter.  Aftertaste is not good.
Pours with a sparkling amber body and an average off-white head.  Mild nutty, caramel with citrus.  Cherry and peach on the front, and vanilla on the back.  Pretty good, but it gets tiresome.
09 Bottle.  Pours deep ruby with a small off-white head.  Lacing is fair.  Burnt nuttiness in the nose carries to the palate and turns to praline pecans with notes of crab apple and herbs.

Pours black, black, black.  No descernible head.  At 13.1%, the alcohol is really well hidden.  Wood, licorice, and charcoal from the nose to the mouth and finished like a port.  A sweet, full, thick beer that just goes on and on...

This pours a large off-white that relaxes into a frothly blanket.  Good lacing and effervescence with an amber color leaning towards orange.  Bread, flowers, pine, leaves and herbs on the nose.  The bread and flowers follow through to the taste and are met with citrus and slight butter.  Beautiful, beautiful beer.  It has strong competition with the BBQ and Imperial Stout, but this may be the best beer Blvd. has ever made.
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - Harvest Dance Wheat Wine

review_blob: Boulevards 2009 release.  What can I say that hasnt already been said?  What a good beer!  It has a small, off-white head.  The lacing is fair.  Cloudy, amber body.  Its toasty and a little musty.  It has cask, wood, and a little smoke.  The alcohol is clearly present, but not necessarily offensive.  Set one aside for a couple of years.
beer_name: Boulevard Smokestack Series - Bourbon Barrel Quad

review_blob: average head and good lacing.  black. roasted malt.  notes of cask, smoke, and licorice.  creamy mouthfeel. very warming and pleasant.
beer_name: Grand Teton Black Cauldron Imperial Stout

review_blob: cherry tootsie pop? average off white head with fair lacing.  the name says it all.  other than that, banana and cola.  a one timer.  a novelty.
It pours an off-white/light brown, diminishing head.  It is medium bodied with burnt chocolate at the fore and slight nuttiness.  Nothing you need to wrap your mind around.
